    "name": "Hemolytic performance acceptability requirement",
    "narrative": "The CFD model shall demonstrate acceptable hemolytic performance across all evaluated operating conditions. Predicted hemolysis indices shall show minimal additional hemolytic burden relative to the predicate device, consistent with recognized good engineering practice for Class II blood-contacting devices. Where model outputs indicate elevated shear stress exposure, the analyst shall confirm that such exposure remains within a reasonable range commensurate with the intended clinical application.",
    "acceptanceCriteria": "Model predictions are considered compliant when hemolytic performance is judged acceptable by the responsible engineer, taking into account the overall trend of results and any recognized hemolysis benchmarking guidance applicable to centrifugal pump geometries. Elevated predictions that remain in a reasonable range relative to predicate performance need not constitute a failure of this requirement."
  },
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
